T1  - Future-Time Framing: The Effect of Language on Corporate Future Orientation
AU  - Liang, Hao
AU  - Marquis, Christopher
AU  - Renneboog, Luc
AU  - Sun, Sunny Li
Y1  - 2018/10/19
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2018/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2018.1217
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2018.1217
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 1093
EP  - 1111
VL  - 29
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We examine how international variation in corporate future-oriented behavior, such as corporate social responsibility and research and development investment, could partially stem from characteristics of the languages spoken at firms. We develop a future-time framing perspective rooted in the literatures on organizational categorization and framing. Our theory and hypotheses focus on how companies with working languages that obligatorily separate the future tense and the present tense engage less in future-oriented behaviors, and this effect is attenuated by exposure to multilingual environments. The results based on a large global sample of firms from 39 countries support our theory, highlighting the importance of language in affecting organizational behavior around the world.The online appendix is available at https://doi.org/10.1287/orsc.2018.1217.
AB  - We examine how international variation in corporate future-oriented behavior, such as corporate social responsibility and research and development investment, could partially stem from characteristics of the languages spoken at firms. We develop a future-time framing perspective rooted in the literatures on organizational categorization and framing. Our theory and hypotheses focus on how companies with working languages that obligatorily separate the future tense and the present tense engage less in future-oriented behaviors, and this effect is attenuated by exposure to multilingual environments. The results based on a large global sample of firms from 39 countries support our theory, highlighting the importance of language in affecting organizational behavior around the world.The online appendix is available at https://doi.org/10.1287/orsc.2018.1217.
